{{unreferenced|date=September 2010}} {{History of the Netherlands}} Historically, many '''Dutch military terms''' have been influential and adopted as [[loanword]]s by many other languages all over the world. Although most of these words are connected to naval activities, some (such as "[[forlorn hope]]") relate to land warfare.
Some Dutch naval terms adopted by the various languages include:
{| class="wikitable" ! From Dutch "boei", from [[Latin]] boia (''shackle'') |- |} {| class="wikitable" ! Language ! Variant |- | '''[[Danish language|Danish]]''' | Bøje |- | '''[[English language|English]]''' | Buoy |- | '''[[Finnish language|Finnish]]''' | Poiju |- | '''[[French language|French]]''' | Bouée |- | '''[[German language|German]]''' | Boje |- | '''[[Italian language|Italian]]''' | Boa |- | '''[[Norwegian language|Norwegian]]''' | Bøye (buoy) |- | '''[[Polish language|Polish]]''' | Boja |- | '''[[Slovak language|Slovak]]''' | Bója |- | '''[[Spanish language|Spanish]]''' | Boya |- | '''[[Swedish language|Swedish]]''' | Boj (Buoy), Boja (Shackle) |- |}
{| class="wikitable" ! From Dutch "kielhalen " meaning ''to drag along the keel'' |- |} {| class="wikitable" ! Language ! Variant |- | '''[[Danish language|Danish]]''' | Kølhaling |- | '''[[English language|English]]''' | Keelhauling |- | '''[[Finnish language|Finnish]]''' | Kölihaalaus (likely borrowed from Swedish form) |- | '''[[German language|German]]''' | Kielholen |- | '''[[Norwegian language|Norwegian]]''' | Kjølhaling |- | '''[[Slovak language|Slovak]]''' | Kýl |- | '''[[Swedish language|Swedish]]''' | Kölhalning |- |}
{| class="wikitable" ! From Dutch "dek " meaning ''"covering"'' |- |} {| class="wikitable" ! Language ! Variant |- | '''[[Danish language|Danish]]''' | Dæk |- | '''[[English language|English]]''' | Deck |- | '''[[German language|German]]''' | Deck |- | '''[[Norwegian language|Norwegian]]''' | Dekk |- | '''[[Swedish language|Swedish]]''' | Däck |- |}
Other words (in [[English language|English]]) include: * Avast, from ''hou vast'', meaning ''hold fast''. * Drill, from the verb '' drillen'', to train/instruct * Freebooter (Pirate), from ''vrijbuiter''. * Yacht, from ''jacht'' meaning ''hunt'' * Pump, from ''pomp''. * Sloop, from ''sloep''. * Skipper, from ''schipper'' meaning someone who ships. * Keel, from ''kiel'' * Maelstrom, from ''maalstroom'' meaning "strong current" (borrowed via a Nordic language) * [[Forlorn hope]], from ''verloren hoop'' "lost hope". * Cruiser, from the verb '' to cruise'' from Dutch ''doorkruisen'' meaning to sail across or go through. * Brandy, from Dutch ''brandewijn'', distilled wine. And many more.
