{{Dutch Grammar}}

'''[[Dutch language|Dutch]] phonology''' is similar to that of other [[West Germanic languages]].

While the spelling of Dutch is officially standardised by an international organisation (the [[Dutch Language Union]]), the pronunciation has no official standard and relies on a ''de facto'' standard documented in reference works such as ''The Phonetics of English and Dutch'' by Beverley Collins and Inger M. Mees,{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003}} ''The Phonology of Dutch'' by Geert Booij,{{sfnp|Booij|1999}} ''Dutch'' by Carlos Gussenhoven,{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|1999}} ''Belgian Standard Dutch'' by Jo Verhoeven{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2005}} or pronunciation dictionaries such as ''{{lang|nl|Uitspraakwoordenboek}}'' ("Pronunciation Dictionary") by Josée Heemskerk and Wim Zonneveld.{{sfnp|Heemskerk|Zonneveld|2000}}

Standard Dutch has two main de facto pronunciation standards: Northern and Belgian. Northern Standard Dutch (henceforth Northern SD) is the most prestigious accent in the Netherlands. It is associated with high status, education and wealth. Even though its speakers seem to be concentrated in the provinces of [[North Holland]], [[South Holland]] and [[Utrecht (province)|Utrecht]] (especially in the [[Randstad]]), it cannot be considered a regional dialect. It is often impossible to tell where its speakers were born or brought up. Belgian Standard Dutch (henceforth Belgian SD) is used by the vast majority of Flemish journalists, which is why it is sometimes called ''VRT-Nederlands'' ("VRT Dutch"; formerly ''BRT-Nederlands'' "BRT Dutch"), after [[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie|VRT]], the national public-service broadcaster for the [[Flemish Region]].{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=4–5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://anw.inl.nl/article/VRT-Nederlands|title=VRT-Nederlands|website=ANW (Algemeen Nederlands Woordenboek)|language=Dutch|access-date=25 March 2017}}</ref>

