* Dutch vowels can be classified as lax and tense,<ref>For example by {{Harvcoltxt|Gussenhoven|1999|p=75}}.</ref> checked and free<ref>For example by {{Harvcoltxt|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=127–128, 132–133}}.</ref> or short and long.<ref>For example by {{Harvcoltxt|Booij|1999|pp=4–5}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Verhoeven|2005|p=245}}.</ref> Phonetically however, the close vowels {{IPA|/i, y, u/}} are as short as the phonological lax/short vowels unless they occur before {{IPA|/r/}}.{{sfnp|Booij|1999|pp=4–6}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=132}}
* Phonologically, {{IPA|/ɪ, ʏ, ʊ/}} can be classified as either close or close-mid. Carlos Gussenhoven classifies them as the former,{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|2007|pp=337, 339}} whereas Geert Booij says that they are the latter and classifies {{IPA|/ɛ, ɔ/}} and the non-native mid vowels as open-mid.{{sfnp|Booij|1999|p=5}}
* {{IPA|/ʏ/}} has been traditionally transcribed with {{angbr|{{IPA|œ}}}}, but modern sources tend to use {{angbr|{{IPA|ʏ}}}} or {{angbr|{{IPA|ɵ}}}} instead.{{sfnp|van Heuven|Genet|2002}}<ref>Sources that use {{angbr|{{IPA|ʏ}}}} include {{Harvcoltxt|Booij|1999|pp=4–5}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Gussenhoven|1999|pp=75–76}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Verhoeven|2005|p=245}}. The online dictionary [http://woorden.org woorden.org] also uses that symbol. Sources that use {{angbr|{{IPA|ɵ}}}} include {{Harvcoltxt|van Reenen|Elias|1998}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Rietveld|van Heuven|2009}}. The traditional transcription of {{angbr|{{IPA|œ}}}} is also used in certain modern sources, for example by {{Harvcoltxt|Kooij|van Oostendorp|2003|p=27}}.</ref> Beverley Collins and Inger Mees write this vowel with {{angbr|{{IPA|ʉ}}}}.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=128}}
* The phonemic status of {{IPA|/ʊ/}} is not clear. Phonetically, a vowel of the {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ʊ|ʊ̞}} ~ {{IPA link|ɔ̝|ɔ̽}}]}}<ref>Described as close-mid {{IPAblink|ʊ|ʊ̞}} by Geert Booij and as mid {{IPAblink|ɔ̝|ɔ̽}} by Beverley Collins and Inger Mees.</ref> type appears before nasals as an allophone of {{IPA|/ɔ/}}, e.g. in ''jong'' {{IPA|[jʊŋ]}} ('young'). This vowel can also be found in certain other words, such as ''op'' {{IPA|[ʊp]}} ('on'), which can form a near-minimal pair with ''mop'' {{IPA|[mɔp]}} ('joke'). This, however, is subject to both individual and geographical variation.{{sfnp|Booij|1999|pp=7, 17}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=97–98}}
* Many speakers feel that {{IPA|/ə/}} and {{IPA|/ʏ/}} belong to the same phoneme, with {{IPAblink|ə}} being its unstressed variant. This is reflected in spelling errors produced by Dutch children, for example {{angbr|binnu}} for ''binnen'' {{IPA|[ˈbɪnə(n)]}} ('inside'). Adding to this, the two vowels have different phonological distribution; for example, {{IPA|/ə/}} can occur word-finally, while {{IPA|/ʏ/}} (along with other lax vowels) cannot. In addition, the word-final allophone of {{IPA|/ə/}} is a close-mid front vowel with some rounding {{IPAblink|ø|ø̜}}, a sound that is similar to {{IPA|/ʏ/}}.{{sfnp|Booij|1999|p=5}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=129}}
* The native tense vowels {{IPA|/eː, øː, oː, aː/}} are long {{IPA|[eː, øː, oː, aː]}} in stressed syllables and short {{IPA|[e, ø, o, a]}} elsewhere. The non-native oral vowels appear only in stressed syllables and thus are always long.{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|2007|pp=342, 344}}
* The native {{IPA|/eː, øː, oː, aː/}} as well as the non-native nasal {{IPA|/ɛ̃ː, œ̃ː, ɔ̃ː, ɑ̃ː/}} are sometimes transcribed without the length marks, as {{angbr|{{IPA|e, ø, o, a, ɛ̃, œ̃, ɔ̃, ɑ̃}}}}.<ref>For example by {{Harvcoltxt|Booij|1999}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Heemskerk|Zonneveld|2000}} as well as the online dictionary [http://www.woorden.org woorden.org].</ref>
* {{IPA|/aː/}}, a phonological back vowel, is central {{IPAblink|äː}} or front {{IPAblink|aː}} in Standard Dutch.{{sfnp|Booij|1999|p=5}}{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|1999|p=76}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=104, 128, 132–133}}{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2005|p=245}}
* The non-native {{IPA|/iː, yː, uː, ɛː, œː, ɔː, ɑː/}} occur only in stressed syllables. In unstressed syllables, they are replaced by the closest native vowel. For instance, verbs corresponding to the nouns ''analyse'' {{Audio-IPA|Nl-analyse.ogg|/aːnaːˈliːzə/|help=no}} ('analysis'), ''centrifuge'' {{Audio-IPA|Nl-centrifuge.ogg|/sɛntriˈfyːzjə/|help=no}} ('spinner'), and ''zone'' {{Audio-IPA|Nl-zone.ogg|/ˈzɔːnə/|help=no}} ('zone') are ''analyseren'' {{Audio-IPA|Nl-analyseren.ogg|/aːnaːliˈzeːrən/|help=no}} ('to analize'), ''centrifugeren'' {{Audio-IPA|Nl-centrifugeren.ogg|/sɛntrifyˈɣeːrən/|help=no}} ('to spin-dry'), and ''zoneren'' {{IPA|/zoːˈneːrən/}} ('to divide into zones').{{sfnp|Booij|1999|pp=6, 16}}
* {{IPA|/œː/}} is extremely rare, and the only words of any frequency in which it occurs are ''oeuvre'' {{Audio-IPA|Nl-oeuvre.ogg|[ˈœːvrə]|help=no}}, ''manoeuvre'' {{Audio-IPA|Nl-manoeuvre.ogg|[maˈnœːvrə]|help=no}} and ''freule''. In the more common words, {{IPA|/ɛː/}} tends to be replaced with the native {{IPA|/ɛ/}}, whereas {{IPA|/ɔː/}} can be replaced by either {{IPA|/ɔ/}} or {{IPA|/oː/}} (Belgians typically select the latter).{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=137–138}}
* The non-native nasal vowels {{IPA|/ɛ̃ː, œ̃ː, ɔ̃ː, ɑ̃ː/}} occur only in loanwords from French.{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|1999|p=75}}{{sfnp|Booij|1999|p=6}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=138}} {{IPA|/ɛ̃ː, ɔ̃ː, ɑ̃ː/}} are often nativized as {{IPA|/ɛn, ɔn, ɑn/}}, {{IPA|/ɛŋ, ɔŋ, ɑŋ/}} or {{IPA|/ɛm, ɔm, ɑm/}}, depending on the place of articulation of the following consonant. For instance, ''restaurant'' {{IPA|/rɛstoːˈrɑ̃ː/}} ('restaurant') and ''pardon'' {{IPA|/pɑrˈdɔ̃ː/}} ('excuse me') are often nativized as {{Audio-IPA|Nl-restaurant.ogg|/rɛstoːˈrɑnt/|help=no}} and {{Audio-IPA|Nl-pardon.ogg|/pɑrˈdɔn/|help=no}}, respectively.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=138}} {{IPA|/œ̃ː/}} is extremely rare, just like its oral counterpart<ref name="some">It is listed by only some sources, namely {{Harvcoltxt|Booij|1999}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Gussenhoven|2007}}.</ref> and the only word of any frequency in which it occurs is ''parfum'' {{IPA|/pɑrˈfœ̃ː/}} ('perfume'), often nativized as {{IPA|/pɑrˈfʏm/}} or {{Audio-IPA|Nl-parfum.ogg|/ˈpɑrfʏm/|help=no}}.
* The non-native {{IPA|/ɑː/}} is listed only by some sources.<ref>Such as {{Harvcoltxt|Booij|1999}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Gussenhoven|2007}}.</ref> It occurs in words such as ''cast'' {{Audio-IPA|Nl-cast.ogg|/kɑːst/|help=no}} ('cast').{{sfnp|Booij|1999|p=6}}{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|2007|p=342}}

The following sections describe the phonetic quality of Dutch monophthongs in detail.

====Close vowels====
* {{IPA|/ɪ/}} is close to the canonical value of the IPA symbol {{angbr|{{IPA|ɪ}}}}.{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|1999|p=76}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=128}} The Standard Belgian realization has also been described as close-mid {{IPAblink|ɪ|ɪ̞}}.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2005|p=245}} In regional SD, the realization may be different: for example, in Antwerp it is closer, more like {{IPAblink|i}}, whereas in places like Dordrecht, Nijmegen, West and East Flanders the vowel is typically more open than the SD counterpart, more like {{IPAblink|e|ë}}. Affected speakers of Northern SD may also use this vowel.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=131}}{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2005|p=246}}
* {{IPA|/i, iː/}} are close front {{IPA|[{{IPA link|i}}, {{IPA link|iː}}]}}, close to cardinal {{IPAblink|i}}.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=132}}{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|1999|p=76}}{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2005|p=245}}
* The majority of sources consider {{IPA|/ʏ/}} to be close-mid central {{IPAblink|ɵ}},{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2005|p=245}}<ref name="vanheuvengenet">{{Harvcoltxt|van Heuven|Genet|2002}}, cited in {{Harvcoltxt|Gussenhoven|2007|pp=337–338}}.</ref>{{sfnp|Rietveld|van Heuven|2009}} yet Beverley Collins and Inger Mees consider it to be close-mid front {{IPAblink|ʏ|ʏ̞}}.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=128}} The study conducted by Vincent van Heuven and Roos Genet has shown that native speakers consider the canonical IPA value of the symbol {{angbr|{{IPA|ɵ}}}} to be the most similar to the Dutch sound, much more similar than the canonical values of {{angbr|{{IPA|ʏ}}}} and {{angbr|{{IPA|œ}}}} (the sound represented by {{angbr|{{IPA|ʉ}}}} was not a part of the study).<ref name="vanheuvengenet"/> In regional SD {{IPA|/ʏ/}} may be raised to near-close {{IPAblink|ɵ̝}}, for example in Amsterdam, Rotterdam and The Hague. In Antwerp, the vowel may be as high as {{IPA|/y/}} and the two vowels may differ in nothing but length. A more open vowel of the {{IPAblink|ɵ̞}}-type is found in southern accents (e.g. in Bruges) and in affected Northern SD.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=131}}{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2005|p=246}}
* {{IPA|/y, yː/}} have been variously described as close front {{IPA|[{{IPA link|y}}, {{IPA link|yː}}]}},{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2005|p=245}}{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|2007|p=338}} near-close front {{IPA|[{{IPA link|y˕}}, {{IPA link|y˕ː}}]}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=132}} and, in Northern SD, near-close central {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ʉ̞}}, {{IPA link|ʉ̞ː}}]}}.{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|1999|p=76}}
* {{IPA|/u, uː/}} are close back {{IPA|[{{IPA link|u}}, {{IPA link|uː}}]}} in Northern SD and close near-back {{IPA|[{{IPA link|u|u̟}}, {{IPA link|u|u̟ː}}]}} in Belgian SD and some varieties of regional SD spoken in Antwerp and Flemish Brabant.{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|1999|p=76}}{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2005|p=245}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=132–133}}

Word-final {{IPA|/i, y, u/}} are raised and end in a voiceless vowel: {{IPA|[ii̥, yẙ, uu̥]}}. The voiceless vowel in the first sequence may sound almost like a palatal fricative {{IPAblink|ç}}.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=132}}

{{IPA|/i, y, u/}} are frequently longer in Belgian SD and most Belgian accents than in Northern SD, in which the length of these vowels is identical to that of lax vowels.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=132}}

Regardless of the exact accent, {{IPA|/i, y, u/}} are mandatorily lengthened to {{IPA|[{{IPA link|iː}}, {{IPA link|yː}}, {{IPA link|uː}}]}} before {{IPA|/r/}} in the same word.{{sfnp|Booij|1999|p=6}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=132}}{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|1999|p=76}} In Northern SD and in Randstad, these are laxed to {{IPA|[i̽ː, y˕ː, u̽ː]}} and often have a schwa-like off-glide ({{IPA|[i̽ə, y˕ə, u̽ə]}}). This means that before {{IPA|/r/}}, {{IPA|/i, y, u/}} are less strongly differentiated from {{IPA|/eː, øː, oː/}} in Northern SD and Randstad than is usually the case in other regional varieties of SD and in Belgian SD.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=132, 134, 200}} There is one exception to the lengthening rule: when {{IPA|/r/}} is followed by a consonant different than {{IPA|/t/}} and {{IPA|/s/}}, {{IPA|/i, y, u/}} remain short. Examples of that are words such as ''wierp'' {{IPA|[ʋirp]}}, ''stierf'' {{IPA|[stirf]}}, ''zwierf'' {{IPA|[zʋirf]}}, ''bedierf'' {{IPA|[bəˈdirf]}}, ''kirsch'' {{IPA|[kirʃ]}} and ''Atatürk'' {{IPA|[ˈaːtaˌtyrk]}}. The rule is also suppressed syllable-finally in certain compounds; compare ''roux-room'' {{IPA|[ˈruroːm]}} with ''roerroom'' {{IPA|[ˈruːr(r)oːm]}} and ''Ruhr-Ohm'' {{IPA|[ˈruːroːm]}}.{{sfnp|Booij|1999|p=6}}{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|2007|pp=344, 347}}

====Mid vowels====
* {{IPA|/ɛ, ɛː/}} are open-mid front {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɛ}}, {{IPA link|ɛː}}]}}.{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|1999|p=76}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=128, 137}} According to Jo Verhoeven, the Belgian SD variants are somewhat raised.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2005|p=245}} Before {{IPA|/n/}} and the velarized or pharyngealized allophone of {{IPA|/l/}}, {{IPA|/ɛ/}} is typically lowered to {{IPAblink|æ}}. In some regional SD (e.g. in Dordrecht, Ghent, Bruges and more generally in Zeeland, North Brabant and Limburg), this lowering is generalized to most or even all contexts. Conversely, some regional SD varieties (e.g. much of Randstad Dutch, especially the Amsterdam dialect as well as the accent of Antwerp) realize the main allophone of {{IPA|/ɛ/}} as higher and more central than open-mid front ({{IPAblink|ɛ̝|ɛ̝̈}}).{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=92, 128–129, 131}}
* {{IPA|/œː/}} is open-mid front {{IPAblink|œː}}.{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|1999|p=76}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=137}}
* {{IPA|/ə/}} has two allophones, with the main one being mid central unrounded {{IPAblink|ə}}. The allophone used in word-final postions resembles the main allophone of {{IPA|/ʏ/}} as it is closer, more front and more rounded ({{IPAblink|ø|ø̜}}).{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=129}}{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|1999|p=76}}
* {{IPA|/ɔ/}} is a very tense, [[Pharyngealization|pharyngealized]] vowel. Its backness has been described as back {{IPAblink|ɔ|ɔˤ}} by Collins and Mees and near-back {{IPAblink|ɔ|ɔ̟ˤ}} by Gussenhoven and Verhoeven. The pharyngeal effect is more pronounced in Northern SD than in the standard Belgian variety. {{IPA|/ɔː/}} is close to {{IPA|/ɔ/}} in terms of height and backness, but it is unclear whether it is has the same secondary articulation of pharyngealization.{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|1999|p=76}}{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2005|p=245}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=128, 132, 137}}

{{IPA|/ɛ, ɔ/}} are typically somewhat lengthened and centralized before {{IPA|/r/}} in Northern SD and Randstad, usually with a slight schwa-like offglide: {{IPA|[ɛ̈ə̆, ɔ̈ə̆]}}. In addition, {{IPA|/ɔ/}} in this position is somewhat less rounded ({{IPA|[ɔ̜̈ə̆]}}) than the main allophone of {{IPA|/ɔ/}}.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=130}}

The free vowels {{IPA|/eː, øː, oː/}} are realized as monophthongs {{IPA|[{{IPA link|eː}}, {{IPA link|øː}}, {{IPA link|oː}}]}} in Belgian SD (Jo Verhoeven describes the Belgian SD realization of {{IPA|/øː/}} as mid central {{IPAblink|ɵ̞ː}}) and in many regional accents. In Northern SD, narrow closing diphthongs {{IPA|[eɪ, øʏ, oʊ]}} are used. The starting point of {{IPA|[oʊ]}} is centralized back ({{IPAblink|o|ö}}), and the starting point of {{IPA|[eɪ]}} has been described as front {{IPAblink|e}} by Collins and Mees and as centralized front {{IPAblink|e|ë}} by Gussenhoven. The monophthongal counterparts of {{IPA|[eɪ, oʊ]}} are peripheral; the former is almost as front as cardinal {{IPAblink|eː}}, whereas the latter is almost as back as cardinal {{IPAblink|oː}}.{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|1999|p=76}}{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2005|p=245}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=108, 110, 133–134}} Many speakers of Randstad Dutch as well as younger speakers of Northern SD realize {{IPA|/eː, øː, oː/}} as rather wide diphthongs of the {{IPA|[ɛɪ, œʏ, ɔʊ]}} type, which may be mistaken for the phonemic diphthongs {{IPA|/ɛi, œy, ɔu/}} by speakers of other accents.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=135}}{{sfnp|Jacobi|2009}} Using {{IPA|[ɛɪ, œʏ, ɔʊ]}} for {{IPA|/eː, øː, oː/}} goes hand in hand with lowering the first elements of {{IPA|/ɛi, œy, ɔu/}} to {{IPA|[aɪ, aʏ, aʊ]}}, a phenomenon termed ''Polder Dutch''. Therefore, the phonemic contrast between {{IPA|/eː, øː, oː/}} and {{IPA|/ɛi, œy, ɔu/}} is still strongly maintained, but its phonetic realization is very different from what one can typically hear in traditional Northern SD.{{sfnp|Stroop|1999}} In Rotterdam and The Hague, the starting point of {{IPA|[oʊ]}} can be fronted to {{IPAblink|ə}} instead of being lowered to {{IPAblink|ɔ}}.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=109–110}}

In Northern SD and in Randstad, {{IPA|/eː, øː, oː/}} lose their closing glides and are raised and slightly centralized to {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɪː}}, {{IPA link|ʏː}}, {{IPA link|ʊː}}]}} (often with a schwa-like off-glide {{IPA|[ɪə, ʏə, ʊə]}}) before {{IPA|/r/}} in the same word. The first two allophones strongly resemble the lax monophthongs {{IPA|/ɪ, ʏ/}}. Dutch children frequently misspell the word ''weer'' ('again') as ''wir''. These sounds may also occur in regional varieties of SD and in Belgian SD, but they are more typically the same as the main allophones of {{IPA|/eː, øː, oː/}} (that is, {{IPA|[{{IPA link|eː}}, {{IPA link|øː}}, {{IPA link|oː}}]}}). An exception to the centralizing rule are syllable-final {{IPA|/eː, øː, oː/}} in compounds such as ''z'''ee'''reis'' {{Audio-IPA|Nl-zeereis.ogg|[ˈzeɪˌrɛis]|help=no}} ('sea voyage'), ''mili'''eu'''ramp'' {{Audio-IPA|Nl-milieuramp.ogg|[mɪlˈjøʏˌrɑmp]|help=no}} ('environmental disaster') and ''bur'''eau'''redactrice'' {{IPA|[byˈroʊredɑkˌtrisə]}} ('desk editor (f.)').{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=131, 134, 200–201}}{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|2007|pp=339, 347}}

In Northern SD, {{IPA|/eː, øː, oː/}} are mid-centralized before the pharyngealized allophone of {{IPA|/l/}}.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=134}}

Several non-standard dialects have retained the distinction between the so-called "sharp-long" and "soft-long" ''e'' and ''o'', a distinction that dates to early [[Middle Dutch]]. The sharp-long varieties originate from the Old Dutch long ''ē'' and ''ō'' (Proto-Germanic ''ai'' and ''au''), while the soft-long varieties arose from short ''i''/''e'' and ''u''/''o'' that were [[Open syllable lengthening|lengthened in open syllables]] in early Middle Dutch. The distinction is not considered to be a part of Standard Dutch and is not recognised in educational materials, but it is still present in many local varieties, such as Antwerpian, [[Limburgish]], [[West Flemish]] and [[Zealandic]]. In these varieties, the sharp-long vowels are often opening diphthongs such as {{IPA|[ɪə, ʊə]}}, while the soft-long vowels are either plain monophthongs {{IPA|[{{IPA link|eː}}, {{IPA link|oː}}]}} or slightly closing {{IPA|[eɪ, oʊ]}}.

====Open vowels====
In Northern SD and some other accents, {{IPA|/ɑ, aː/}} are realised so that the former is a back vowel {{IPAblink|ɑ}}, whereas the latter is central {{IPAblink|äː}} or front {{IPAblink|aː}}. In Belgian SD {{IPA|/aː/}} is also central or front, but {{IPA|/ɑ/}} may be central {{IPAblink|ä}} instead of back {{IPAblink|ɑ}}, so it may have the same backness as {{IPA|/aː/}}.{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|1999|p=76}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=104, 128, 132–133}}{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2005|p=245}}

Other accents may have different realisations:
* Many accents (Amsterdam, Utrecht, Antwerp) realize this pair with 'inverted' backness, so that {{IPA|/ɑ/}} is central {{IPAblink|ä}} (or, in the case of Utrecht, even front {{IPAblink|a}}), whereas {{IPA|/aː/}} is closer to cardinal {{IPAblink|ɑː}}.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=131, 133}}
* Outside the Randstad, fronting of {{IPA|/ɑ/}} to central {{IPAblink|ä}} is very common. On the other hand, in Rotterdam and Leiden, the short {{IPA|/ɑ/}} sounds even ''darker'' than the Standard Northern realization, being realized as a fully back and raised open vowel, unrounded {{IPAblink|ɑ|ɑ̝}} or rounded {{IPAblink|ɒ|ɒ̝}}.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=132}}
* In Groningen, {{IPA|/aː/}} tends to be particularly front, similar to the quality of the cardinal vowel {{IPAblink|aː}}, whereas in The Hague and in the affected Standard Northern accent, {{IPA|/aː/}} may be raised and fronted to {{IPAblink|æː}}, particularly before {{IPA|/r/}}.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=133}}

Before {{IPA|/r/}}, {{IPA|/ɑ/}} is typically a slight centering diphthong with a centralized first element ({{IPA|[ɐə̆]}}) in Northern SD and in Randstad.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=130}}

===Diphthongs===
[[Image:Dutch diphthong chart.svg|thumb|upright=1.13|[[Diphthong]]s of Northern SD, from {{Harvcoltxt|Gussenhoven|1999|p=76}}]]
[[Image:Belgian Dutch diphthongs chart.svg|thumb|upright=1.13|Diphthongs of Belgian SD, from {{Harvcoltxt|Verhoeven|2005|p=245}}]]
[[Image:Dutch tense backing diphthongs on a vowel chart.svg|thumb|upright=1.13|Dutch tense backing diphthongs, from {{Harvcoltxt|Collins|Mees|2003|p=137}}]]
[[Image:Dutch tense fronting diphthongs on a vowel chart.svg|thumb|upright=1.13|Dutch tense fronting diphthongs, from {{Harvcoltxt|Collins|Mees|2003|p=137}}]]
Dutch also has several diphthongs, but only three of them are indisputably phonemic. All of them end in a non-syllabic close vowel {{IPA|[i̯, y̑, u̯]}} (henceforth written {{IPA|[i, y, u]}} for simplicity), but they may begin with a variety of other vowels.

