| {{IPA|ɔu}}
|}

* {{IPA|/ɔu/}} has been variously transcribed with {{angbr|{{IPA|ɔu}}}},<ref>For example by {{Harvcoltxt|Booij|1999|pp=4, 6}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Verhoeven|2005|p=245}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Gussenhoven|2007|p=340}}.</ref> {{angbr|{{IPA|ɑu}}}},<ref>For example by {{Harvcoltxt|Collins|Mees|2003|p=135}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Kooij|van Oostendorp|2003|p=28}}.</ref> and {{angbr|{{IPA|ʌu}}}}.<ref>For example by {{Harvcoltxt|Gussenhoven|1999|p=76}}.</ref>
* The starting points of {{IPA|/ɛi, œy, ɔu/}} tend to be closer ({{IPA|[ɛɪ, œ̈ʏ, ɔ̈ʊ]}}) in Belgian SD than in Northern SD ({{IPA|[ɛ̞ɪ, œ̞̈ʏ, ʌ̞̈ʊ]}}). In addition, the Belgian SD realization of {{IPA|/ɔu/}} tends to be fully rounded, unlike the typical Northern SD realization of the vowel. However, Jo Verhoeven reports rather open starting points of the Belgian SD variants of {{IPA|/œy, ɔu/}} ({{IPA|[œ̞̈ʏ, ɔ̞̈ʊ]}}), so the main difference between Belgian and Northern SD in that regard may be only in the rounding of the first element of {{IPA|/ɔu/}}, but the fully rounded variant of {{IPA|/ɔu/}} is also used by some Netherlands speakers, particularly of the older generation. It is also used in most of Belgium, in agreement with the Belgian SD realization.{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|1999|p=76}}{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2005|p=245}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=135–136}}
* In conservative Northern SD, the starting points of {{IPA|/ɛi, œy, ɔu/}} are open-mid and rounded in the case of the last two vowels: {{IPA|[ɛɪ, œʏ, ɔʊ]}}.{{sfnp|Stroop|1999}}
* The backness of the starting point of the Belgian SD realization of {{IPA|/ɛi/}} has been variously described as front {{IPA|[ɛɪ]}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=135}} and centralized front {{IPA|[ɛ̈ɪ]}}.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2005|p=245}}
* In ''Polder Dutch'' spoken in some areas of the Netherlands (especially Randstad and its surroundings), the starting points of {{IPA|/ɛi, œy, ɔu/}} are further lowered to {{IPA|[aɪ, aʏ, aʊ]}} to facilitate the pronunciation. This typically goes hand in hand with lowering the starting points of {{IPA|/eː, øː, oː/}} to {{IPA|[ɛɪ, œʏ, ɔʊ]}}. These realizations have existed in [[Hollandic dialect|Hollandic]] dialects since the 16th century and now are becoming standard in the Netherlands. They are an example of a [[chain shift]] akin to the [[Great Vowel Shift]]. According to Jan Stroop, the fully lowered variant of {{IPA|/ɛi/}} is the same as the phonetic diphthong {{IPA|[aːi]}}, making ''bij'' 'at' and ''baai'' 'bay' perfect homophones.{{sfnp|Stroop|1999}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=136}}
* The rounding of the starting point of the Northern SD realization of {{IPA|/œy/}} has been variously described as slight {{IPA|[œ̜ʏ]}}{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|2007|p=340}} and nonexistent {{IPA|[ɐ̜ʏ]}}.{{sfnp|Rietveld|van Heuven|2009}} The unrounded variant has also been reported to occur in many other accents, for example Leiden, Rotterdam and in some Belgian speakers.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=136}}
* Phonetically, the ending points of the native diphthongs are lower and more central than cardinal {{IPA|[{{IPA link|i}}, {{IPA link|y}}, {{IPA link|u}}]}}, i.e. more like {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɪ}}, {{IPA link|ʏ}}, {{IPA link|ʊ}}]}} or even {{IPA|[{{IPA link|e}}, {{IPA link|ø}}, {{IPA link|o}}]}} (however, Jo Verhoven reports a rather close ({{IPAblink|i|ï}}) ending point of the Belgian SD variant of {{IPA|/ɛi/}}, so this might be somewhat variable). In Belgian SD, the ending points are shorter than in Northern SD, but in both varieties the glide is an essential part of the articulation. Furthermore, in Northern SD there is no appreciable difference between the ending points of {{IPA|/ɛi, œy, ɔu/}} and the phonetic diphthongs {{IPA|[eɪ, øʏ, oʊ]}}, with both sets ending in vowels close to {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɪ}}, {{IPA link|ʏ}}, {{IPA link|ʊ}}]}}.{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|1999|p=76}}{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2005|p=245}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=127, 135}}
* In some regional varieties of SD (Southern, regional Belgian), the ending points of {{IPA|/ɛi, œy, ɔu/}} are even lower than in Standard Dutch: {{IPA|[ɛe̞, œø̞, ɔo̞ ~ ʌo̞]}}, and in the traditional [[The Hague dialect|dialect of The Hague]] they are pure monophthongs {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɛː}}, {{IPA link|œː}}, {{IPA link|ɑː}}]}}. Broad Amsterdam speakers can also monophthongize {{IPA|/ɛi/}}, but to {{IPAblink|aː}}. It typically does not merge with {{IPA|/aː/}} as that vowel has a rather back ({{IPAblink|ɑː}}) realization in Amsterdam.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=133, 136}}

Apart from {{IPA|[eɪ, øʏ, oʊ]}} which occur only in Northern SD and regional Netherlands SD, all varieties of SD have phonetic diphthongs {{IPA|[iu, yu, ui, eːu, ɔi, oːi, ɑi, aːi]}}. Phonemically, they are considered to be sequences of {{IPA|/iʋ, yʋ, uj, eːʋ, ɔj, oːj, ɑj, aːj/}} by Geert Booij and as monosyllabic sequences {{IPA|/iu, yu, ui, eːu, oːi, aːi/}} by Beverley Collins and Inger Mees (they do not comment on {{IPA|[ɔi]}} and {{IPA|[ɑi]}}).{{sfnp|Booij|1999|pp=5, 44}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=134–137}} This article adopts the former analysis.

In Northern SD, the second elements of {{IPA|[iu, yu, eːu]}} can be labiodental {{IPA|[iʋ, yʋ, eːʋ]}}. This is especially common in intervocalic positions.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|p=137}}

In Northern SD and regional Netherlands SD, the close-mid elements of {{IPA|[eːu, oːi]}} may be subject to the same kind of diphthongization as {{IPA|/eː, oː/}}, so they may be actually triphthongs with two closing elements {{IPA|[eɪu, oʊi]}} ({{IPA|[eːu]}} can instead be {{IPA|[eɪʋ]}}, a closing diphthong followed by {{IPA|[ʋ]}}). In Rotterdam, {{IPA|[oːi]}} can be phonetically {{IPA|[əʊi]}}, with a central starting point.{{sfnp|Booij|1999|p=44}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=112, 136–137}}

{{IPA|[aːi]}} is realized with more prominence on the first element according to Booij and with equal prominence on both elements according to Collins and Mees. Other diphthongs have more prominence on the first element.{{sfnp|Booij|1999|p=44}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=136–137}}

The ending points of these diphthongs are typically somewhat more central ({{IPA|[ï, ü]}}) than cardinal {{IPA|[i, u]}}. They tend to be higher than the ending points of the phonemic diphthongs {{IPA|/ɛi, œy, ɔu/}}.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2003|pp=135–137}}

